{{Infobox book| | name = Armenian Golgotha | image = armenian_golgotha_cover.jpg | author = [[Grigoris Balakian]] | cover_artist = | country = [[Germany]] (1922), [[France]] (1959) | language = [[Armenian language|Armenian]] | series = | genre = Memoir | publisher = [[Vintage Books]] | release_date = 1922 & 1959 | english_pub_date = 2009 | media_type = | pages = 509 | isbn = 978-1-4000-9677-0 | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} '''Armenian Golgotha''' ({{lang-hy|Հայ Գողգոթան}}) is a memoir written by [[Grigoris Balakian]] about his eyewitness account of the [[Armenian Genocide]]. The memoir was released in two volumes.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Whittemore|first1=Katharine|title=Seven books on the Armenian genocide - The Boston Globe|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/2015/09/25/seven-books-armenian-genocide/vXumdvQTsNR061mOupX7xJ/story.html|accessdate=23 June 2016|work=BostonGlobe.com|date=25 September 2015}}</ref> Volume 1, about his life prior to and during the Armenian Genocide, was released in 1922. Volume 2, about his life as a fugitive after the Genocide, was released in 1959. Originally published in [[Armenian language|Armenian]], the memoir was later published in various languages including an English translation by [[Peter Balakian]], Balakian's great-nephew, with Aris Sevag.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Romano|first1=Carlin|title="Armenian Golgotha: A Memoir of the Armenian Genocide, 1915-18" by Grigoris Balakian|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/lifestyles/books/chi-books-review-armenian-golgotha-memoir-balakian-story.html|accessdate=23 June 2016|work=Chicago Tribune|date=12 April 2010}}</ref>
== Reception == Upon the release of the English translation in 2009, many publications reviewed the account. ''[[The New Yorker]]'' referred to the account as "a fascinating first-hand testimony to a monumental crime."<ref>{{cite news|last1=Davidson|first1=Amy|title=Armenian Golgotha|url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2009/05/04/armenian-golgotha|accessdate=23 June 2016|work=The New Yorker|date=4 May 2009}}</ref> [[Elie Wiesel]], the author best known for the novel [[Night (book)|Night]], referred to the account as "heartbreaking" because he believes that the memory presented by Balakian "must remain a lesson for more than one generation".<ref>{{cite web|title=Early Praise From Elie Wiesel and Others for Grigoris Balakian’s Armenian Golgotha: A Memoir of The Armenian Genocide|url=http://asbarez.com/60401/early-praise-from-elie-wiesel-and-others-for-grigoris-balakians-armenian-golgotha-a-memoir-of-the-armenian-genocide/|website=Asbarez.com|accessdate=23 June 2016|date=13 March 2009}}</ref> ''[[The New Republic]]'' praised the account as "a powerful and important book" because "it takes place as one of the key first-hand sources for understanding the Armenian Genocide".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Republic|first1=The New|title=The Evil That Men Do|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/62933/the-evil-men-do|accessdate=23 June 2016|work=New Republic|date=1 July 2009}}</ref> Writing for ''[[The Washington Post]]'', [[Chris Bohjalian]] (a second-generation Armenian American) felt personally connected by understanding what happened to his great-grandparents. Bohjalian opined that Balakian's account was "rich with evidence of the Turkish government's complicity and its leaders' premeditation." Bohjalian also hoped that the account would be widely read.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bohjalian|first1=Chris|title=A Deadly Time Brought to Life|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/04/03/AR2009040301894.html|work=Washington Post|accessdate=28 November 2017|date=5 April 2009}}</ref>
