'''Ioannis Kakridis''' ({{lang-el|Ιωάννης Κακριδής}}) (17 November 1901 – 20 March 1992) was a [[Greece|Greek]] classical scholar.

He was born in [[Athens]] in 1901 and received his PhD at the [[University of Athens]]. He went on to become a professor at the universities of [[University of Athens|Athens]], [[University of Thessaloniki|Thessaloniki]], [[University of Tübingen|Tübingen]], [[Stockholm University|Stockholm]], [[Lund University|Lund]] and [[Uppsala University|Uppsala]]. Kakridis was a Homer scholar and one of the most important classicists of twentieth-century Greece. He was also an early and staunch advocate of the adoption of the [[Greek diacritics|monotonic system]] in the Greek language. In 1941, he was denounced by the faculty of the University of Athens for republishing a lecture in the monotonic system, which led to the so-called "Trial of Accents" and his suspension and later dismissal from the university.<ref>Demaras, K. Th., ''A History of Modern Greek Literature'', trans. by Mary Gianos (London 1974) ii. 193–97, cited in {{citation |last=Papaioannou |first=Sophia |title=Translating Homer in 20th century Greece: the 'Silent' Voice of a Revolution |url=http://www.class.uh.edu/mcl/faculty/armstrong/papa.draft.html#f9 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080505035839/http://www.class.uh.edu/mcl/faculty/armstrong/papa.draft.html#f9 |archivedate=5 May 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

The list of his written work is quite extensive. The most important works are a translation into the [[modern Greek language]] of the works of [[Homer]], together with [[Nikos Kazantzakis]] and a five-volume collection of Greek mythology.

